TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Cost-Based Methodology for Stochastic Line Balancing with Intermittent Line Stoppages
AU  - Silverman, Fred N.
AU  - Carter, John C.
Y1  - 1986/04/01
PY  - 1986
DA  - 1986/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.32.4.455
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.32.4.455
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 455
EP  - 463
VL  - 32
IS  - 4
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper examines the effect of stochastic task times on the total operating costs of a continuously paced assembly line under the assumption that the line is stopped whenever at least one work station requires more time than allotted. A comprehensive stochastic cost function is integrated into an efficient balancing algorithm to enable an approximately minimum cost balance to be obtained. An experiment was conducted to determine the cost savings resulting from using the stochastic method as compared to two deterministic methods. The stochastic method of this paper produced lower cost balances in most cases studied.
AB  - This paper examines the effect of stochastic task times on the total operating costs of a continuously paced assembly line under the assumption that the line is stopped whenever at least one work station requires more time than allotted. A comprehensive stochastic cost function is integrated into an efficient balancing algorithm to enable an approximately minimum cost balance to be obtained. An experiment was conducted to determine the cost savings resulting from using the stochastic method as compared to two deterministic methods. The stochastic method of this paper produced lower cost balances in most cases studied.
